      <hedline>
        <hl1>Raines Readies For Olympics</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Tim Raines to play four games with Somerset Patriots of independent Atlantic League in preparation for play with United States Olympic baseball team (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Tim Raines, who announced his retirement in March after 21 seasons in the major leagues, is set to join the Somerset Patriots of Bridgewater, N.J., who play in the independent Atlantic League.</p>
        <p>Raines, 41, will play four games from July 17-20 in preparation for the United States team at the Olympics in Sydney, Australia.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Tim Raines, who announced his retirement in March after 21 seasons in the major leagues, is set to join the Somerset Patriots of Bridgewater, N.J., who play in the independent Atlantic League.</p>
        <p>Raines, 41, will play four games from July 17-20 in preparation for the United States team at the Olympics in Sydney, Australia.</p>
        <p>Raines, a seven-time All-Star and .295 career hitter, finished fourth on the career list with 807 stolen bases. He played with the Montreal Expos, the Chicago White Sox, the Yankees and the Oakland Athletics. His 1999 season with Oakland was cut short by lupus.</p>
        <p>He won World Series titles with the Yankees in 1996 and 1998.</p>
      </block>
